 the study shows that although attempts to govern Quebec by educating its population consumed huge amounts of public money, they had little impact on rural ignorance: while near-universal literacy reigned in New England by the 1820s, at best one in three French-speaking peasant men in Quebec could sign his name in the insurrectionary decade of the 1830s. Curtis documents educational conditions on the ground, but also shows how imperial attempts to govern a tumultuous colony propelled the early development of Canadian social science. He provides a revisionist account of the pioneering investigations of Lord Gosford and Lord Durham.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEducationxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy18th century. 0aEducationxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy19th century. 0aEducationxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy18th century. 0aEducationxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province)xHistoryy19th century. 0aEducationzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy18th century. 0aEducationzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy19th century. 0aEducationzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy18th century. 0aEducationzQuébec (Province)xHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268668740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442686687423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442686687.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK